      "blocks": {
        "rich_text_rJaBdp": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "name": "Introduction",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<p>Vintage jewellery has a certain charm that modern designs sometimes struggle to recreate. When you look closely at an antique-style ring, you’ll often notice delicate details around the edges or on the band. These small touches -tiny bead-like borders, lace-like metal patterns, or hand-carved designs - are what give vintage rings their character.</p><p>Three of the most recognizable techniques used in vintage jewellery are milgrain, filigree, and engraving. While they may look decorative, each of these details reflects a long tradition of craftsmanship that has been used in jewellery making for generations.</p><p>Today, many jewellery lovers are rediscovering these techniques because they add personality and depth to rings. At Lucira Jewelry, vintage-inspired designs such as the Vintage Halo Oval Diamond Ring, Round Solitaire Vintage Engagement Ring, and Regency Bloom Diamond Ring highlight these timeless details while using modern diamonds and materials.</p><p>Let’s take a closer look at what these vintage techniques actually mean.</p>",
            "custom_id": "",
            "text_alignment": "left"
          }
        },
        "rich_text_qw7HLy": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "name": "What Is Milgrain and Why It Adds a Soft Vintage Edge to Rings",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<h2>What Is Milgrain and Why It Adds a Soft Vintage Edge to Rings</h2>",
            "custom_id": "what-is",
            "text_alignment": "left"
          }
        },
        "rich_text_A8fUE6": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "name": "Rich Text ",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<p>Milgrain is one of the most recognizable elements in vintage jewellery. The word comes from the French phrase <em>“mille-grain,”</em> which means “a thousand grains.”</p><p>In jewellery design, milgrain refers to a row of tiny metal beads placed along the edges of a ring or around a diamond setting. These small dots may look simple, but they create a soft, antique feel that immediately makes a ring look more refined.</p><p>Milgrain details were especially popular during the Edwardian and Art Deco periods, when jewellery makers focused on intricate finishing.</p><p>A ring like the Round Solitaire Vintage Engagement Ring often includes milgrain along the edges of the band or around the setting. This small detail frames the diamond and gives the ring a delicate, old-world look.</p><p>Even though milgrain is subtle, it can completely change how a ring feels.</p>",
            "custom_id": "color",
            "text_alignment": "left"
          }
        },
        "rich_text_AJHQPB": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "name": "What Filigree Work Means and Why It Looks Like Jewelry Lace",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<h2>What Filigree Work Means and Why It Looks Like Jewelry Lace</h2>",
            "custom_id": "what-filigree",
            "text_alignment": "left"
          }
        },
        "rich_text_bhGzpc": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "name": "Rich Text",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<p>Filigree is one of the most artistic techniques in jewellery making. Instead of a solid metal band, filigree designs use thin metal wires shaped into delicate patterns.</p><p>These patterns often resemble lace, vines, or small scrolls.</p><p>Filigree became very popular during the Victorian and Art Deco eras, when jewellery designs focused heavily on craftsmanship and ornamentation.</p><p>A ring like the Regency Bloom Diamond Ring reflects this kind of artistic inspiration. While the center diamond remains the focus, the metalwork around it adds depth and texture to the overall design.</p><p>Because filigree patterns are intricate, they give rings a romantic and slightly antique appearance.</p><p>Many people choose filigree rings when they want something that feels elegant but also distinctive.</p>",
            "custom_id": "clarity",
            "text_alignment": "left"
          }
        },
        "rich_text_qwTzXx": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "name": "How Hand Engraving Adds Personal Character to Vintage Rings",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<h2>How Hand Engraving Adds Personal Character to Vintage Rings</h2>",
            "custom_id": "how-hand",
            "text_alignment": "left"
          }
        },
        "rich_text_mEE3FU": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "name": "Rich Text ",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<p>These designs may include:<br/><br/>1.] Floral patterns<br/>2.] Geometric shapes<br/>3.] Scrollwork or vines<br/>4.] Personal messages or initials<br/><br/>In the past, engraving was done entirely by hand. Skilled artisans would carve the designs carefully using specialized tools.</p><p>Today, some vintage-inspired rings still feature engraved details to recreate that handcrafted feel.</p><p>For example, a design like the Vintage Halo Oval Diamond Ring often includes subtle engraving on the band that adds depth without distracting from the diamond.</p><p>These details may not be obvious at first glance, but they give the ring personality.</p>",
            "custom_id": "",
            "text_alignment": "left"
          }
        },
        "rich_text_9LDfB8": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "name": "Why These Vintage Techniques Still Matter Today",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<h2>Why These Vintage Techniques Still Matter Today</h2>",
            "custom_id": "why-these",
            "text_alignment": "left"
          }
        },
        "rich_text_MiPVCX": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<p>Milgrain, filigree, and engraving are not just decorative features. They represent the kind of craftsmanship that made antique jewellery so special.</p><p>In earlier times, jewellery was often created slowly by skilled artisans rather than mass-produced. These techniques required patience and attention to detail.</p><p>Today, vintage-inspired designs bring that craftsmanship into modern jewellery.</p><p>Many people are drawn to these details because they make a ring feel more meaningful. Instead of a plain band, the ring carries subtle textures and patterns that tell a story.</p>",
            "custom_id": "",
            "text_alignment": "left"
          }
        },
        "rich_text_CMRgT8": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "name": "Vintage Craftsmanship Meets Modern Diamond Jewelry",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<h2>Vintage Craftsmanship Meets Modern Diamond Jewelry</h2>",
            "custom_id": "vintage-craftsmanship",
            "text_alignment": "left"
          }
        },
        "rich_text_e3fJNY": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<p>While vintage designs may look old-world, they are often paired with modern materials and techniques.</p><p>At Lucira Jewelry, vintage-inspired rings combine traditional design elements with IGI-certified lab-grown diamonds. This approach allows customers to enjoy the romance of vintage jewellery while still benefiting from modern diamond quality and ethical sourcing.</p><p>Designs like the Vintage Halo Oval Diamond Ring and the Regency Bloom Diamond Ring show how classic craftsmanship can blend beautifully with contemporary jewellery design.</p><p>The result is a ring that feels timeless rather than outdated.</p>",
            "custom_id": "",
            "text_alignment": "left"
          }
        },
        "rich_text_NWFwDz": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "name": "Why Many Buyers Are Rediscovering Vintage Details",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<h2>Why Many Buyers Are Rediscovering Vintage Details</h2>",
            "custom_id": "why-many",
            "text_alignment": "left"
          }
        },
        "rich_text_xkPjq4": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<p>In recent years, many jewellery buyers have moved away from overly simple designs. Instead, they are looking for rings with character.</p><p>Vintage techniques like milgrain, filigree, and engraving add exactly that.</p><p>These details create a sense of artistry that you don’t often see in modern minimalist rings. They also help a ring stand out without needing a large diamond or heavy design.</p><p>For people who appreciate craftsmanship and subtle elegance, vintage-style rings offer something truly special.</p>",
            "custom_id": "",
            "text_alignment": "left"
          }
        }
      },
